  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a **felony** under both federal and state laws in the United States. Money laundering involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear lawful. This crime is taken very seriously because it enables the continuation of illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and organized crime.\n\n### **Federal Penalties**  \nUnder federal law (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957), money laundering can result in:  \n- Fines of up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater.  \n- Prison sentences of up to **20 years** per count.  \n\n### **State Penalties**  \nState penalties vary but often include significant prison time and hefty fines, depending on the amount of money laundered and the severity of the offense.\n\n### **Civil Penalties**  \nIn addition to criminal penalties, individuals or entities involved in money laundering may face civil forfeiture of assets derived from or used in the illegal activity.\n\n### **Who Can Be Charged?**  \nAnyone involved in the process of money laundering can be charged, including individuals, business owners, financial institutions, and even professionals like lawyers or accountants who knowingly facilitate the laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious felony with severe legal consequences, including substantial prison time, fines, and asset forfeiture.",
